1. The PR removes the session-based `getCompressionCodec(session)` and instead reads from `tableMetadata.getProperties()` via `IcebergTableProperties.getCompressionCodec()`
2. The PR adds a new `getHiveCompressionCodec()` method that reads the compression codec from storage properties
3. The PR adds special handling for Parquet: when compression is not explicitly set, it sets `PARQUET_COMPRESSION` to an empty string `""` to prevent Iceberg's default `zstd`

From the PR diff, in the new `createTableProperties` method:
```java
// Iceberg will set write.parquet.compression-codec to zstd by default if this property is not set: https://github.com/trinodb/trino/issues/20401,
// but we don't want to set this property if this is not explicitly set by customer via set table properties.
if (!(fileFormat == PARQUET && compressionCodec.isPresent())) {
    propertiesBuilder.put(PARQUET_COMPRESSION, "");
}
```

And after the transaction is created:
```java
// If user doesn't set compression-codec for parquet, we need to remove write.parquet.compression-codec property,
// Otherwise Iceberg will set write.parquet.compression-codec to zstd by default.
String parquetCompressionValue = transaction.table().properties().get(PARQUET_COMPRESSION);
if (parquetCompressionValue != null && parquetCompressionValue.isEmpty()) {
    transaction.updateProperties()
            .remove(PARQUET_COMPRESSION)
            .commit();
}
```

So the PR explicitly:
1. Sets `write.parquet.compression-codec=""` (empty string) when the file format is not Parquet OR when compression codec is not explicitly set


2. Then removes the empty property from the transaction

